segments.text: And I don't know, maybe I shouldn't say this, but I don't know whether Joe was a political high or not, because his brother was president of Corpus Christi State at the time, and was kind of the fair-haired lad of the system, I think.
But then in...
Oh, yeah, it was November the 8th.
I'll never forget it.
I'd been trying to get one of my supervisors reclassified.
We'd gotten into the sign business by that time, and I had a graphics supervisor, and I was afraid I was going to lose him if I didn't get him reclassified.
And I'd been trying to get a meeting with Robert for two and a half months to talk about it.
because you didn't do anything like that without Robert's blessings right off the top.
You know, it had
Had to go up and then had to come back around and through.
And so I went up to visit with Robert and had all my stuff.
And he was up in Rudder Tower at his office and had a little conference table right by the entrance to his office.
And he was over by the window and he said, go ahead and sit down.
So I sat down and spread my stuff out.
And he came over and he said, I'm going to merge grounds and physical plant.
and pitched a packet over to me, sliding across the table, and said, there's your new job.
I said, oh?
He said, yeah.
And I said, Robert, you don't fix something unless it's broke, and we sure as hell aren't broke.
He said, well, that's what I'm going to do.

and uh so i you know was shocked i mean because i thought robert and i had gotten along very well but and i never did understand a lot of the why of it but i wound up as deputy director of physical plant in november of 90. i went to talk to joe sugg and
all like that, and he didn't want to talk to me a whole lot, you know.
I spent from November until September, I didn't do a thing.
Now, was this a, as you understood it, was this a promotion?
Well, Joe says it was.
Joe Sugg said it was, and I said, well, I don't see how you can call it a promotion, you know.
And I went to, I don't know whether you remember Leroy Johnson or not, he was assistant director of fiscal planning over the fiscal, and Leroy and I had known each other for years.
And I kept going to him, I said, you know, when the budgets come up, I want to see if my job's in the budget.
Because I had some strong premonition that my title would not be in the budget.
But it was.
I'd talk to my son, who's an attorney, to see what, because I'd never gotten anything but commendations and all like this.
And I didn't think they could fire me, but I didn't think they had any kind of grounds.

So then Joe decided that I guess that I wasn't going anywhere and that he needed to get me doing something so we had had developed a geographic information system and so he put me put the geographic information system under me which was kind of a godsend because that was something that I liked I knew what it was about you could see the value of it and trying to get that get that going so I had that and
Oh, I did a few other little things, but I was explicitly kept out of anything I'd been involved in for the last 25 or 30 years.
And nobody ever gave you any explanation?
And a sub would threaten me and say, you talk to Robert Smith and I'll fire you on the spot.
He told anybody that.
Nobody went up above him.
And then Robert served for how much longer?
Well, he served until early 94.
He and Joe got involved.
We needed some additional generation capacity.
And so they got this thing about a third-party generation power plant.
And unfortunately, you know, I wouldn't wish this on anybody.
Robert got sick.
You know, he developed, I guess, prostate cancer.
And he got to the point that he couldn't handle everything.
You know, he was away.
He just couldn't do it.
And Sugg was way out.
He'd gotten permission from Robert, I guess, too.
And I think Robert was working on pretty direct orders from Margraves, who was chairman of the board at that time.
And then things kind of went
started coming apart after this, because this was kind of a design and build thing, and nobody was supervising them.
They were tearing stuff up and all like this.
And the upshot was that in probably June,
Well, I guess Ray Bowen had come by then.
And then by June, May or June of, I think, yeah, it was 94, he replaced Robert.
And then it wasn't too long until they replaced Joe, asked Joe to move aside.
This was after Jerry Gaston was named interim vice president.
And I'd known Jerry a long time.
And so...
In late August of that year, Jerry, he called me and said, would you be interim director of physical plant for about 60 days till we can find somebody?
I said, okay.
He said, are you interested?
I said, no, it's a doable job, but I'm who I am.
I'm a green person.
I need to be dealing with stuff that I've dealt with for the last 30 or 40 years.

And so then we had all sorts of problems with utilities and we had to, we had to, uh, the state management audit was going, had just been initiated and, um, a number of areas, you know, they were looking at a number of utilities was one of them and they'd gotten, I think,
Probably 80% of the, they had an 800 number, and about 80% of the 800 calls they got was from the Department of Utilities.
I mean, it was, we had a gentleman by the name of Al Baxter that Joe had hired, and I think Al was probably a pretty good engineer.
He had hired another guy that was not too swift.
I mean, his personnel dealings were just,
but at any rate, there were a lot of complaints there, and so I was having to respond to a lot of these questions, and in the meantime, Leroy Johnson had retired on me, so I had,
I had my old job, what little was my old job, the director's job, and Leroy's job, you know.
And I dealt with Jerry, and I got to know Jerry, I knew Jerry pretty well, but I got to really know Jerry real well.
You know, we worked, oh God, we worked so closely together.
And responding to all this, and then it became relevant that we had a problem in utilities.
So in early January,
of 95, we put both Al Baxter and Don Thompson, was the guy's name, on administrative leave with pay because there was just so much there we had to investigate.
And then we appointed a three-person committee to look into it.
And they did all their looking and all like this.
and came back and we decided there was grounds and Al Baxter in the meantime had decided he needed to go elsewhere and so he saw the handwriting on the wall but they were, I had told them

me back up a little bit on normally during Christmas break we would do some chill water outages to do maintenance and this kind of thing because that's about the only time of the year that you've got a clear shot at people not being in buildings or at least very few people and so they were also working on a
an in-house project that Joe had, and I was just getting into some of this, that he had let them do.
They were going to split the chill water system into four distinct systems.
which bothered me.
And they were going to put some, and they'd bought four 900 horsepower turbine pumps to put one on each thing.
And Estill called me and said, they're going to blow the place up, Gene.
They're going to blow it up because he'd gotten wind of it.
And I respect Joe.
Joe's a very good engineer.
And so I canceled the outage because I knew they were going to do some work on these pumps as a part of that.
And so then they came up and met with me and they said, we've got to have an outage or we can't guarantee chill water next year.
I said, okay, you go ahead and have your outage, but do not do anything in support of the big pumping system.
Period.
And apparently they did.
And as the investigation team turned up, they did almost 500 contract millwright man hours in direct support of those pumps.
You know, I mean, huge pipe welding and all like this.
And I told Jerry, I said, you know, if I had known they were working on that during Christmas, I'd have gone out and fired both of them on the spot.
And he said, yeah, I think I'd have been right behind you.
But
Anyway, we had to work through that.
And then ultimately, Don Thompson sued both.
That's still going on, I guess.
I don't know.
I hear from the lawyers every now and then.
And so my 60 days as interim ended on the last of August.
exactly a year afterwards when Chuck Scipio came.
And then I worked for Chuck for a while.
And Jerry had asked me if I wanted to apply for it.
And I said, no, I think I'm going to retire before long.
And whoever gets it needs some years in the job.
And I said, at that point in time, I still had some
that they might break grounds back out or that I might get back into some of that.
And that's where I was headed.
But that didn't happen.
So you retired when?
I retired in February of 98.
February of 98.
Yeah, it was 25 years to the day.
Exactly a quarter century.
Yeah.
Let's see, did you ever have any system responsibilities?
No, not delineated.
I'd gotten to the point in my relationship, even after the merger, Joe Sugg didn't like this, but they would call and say, we need some help.
And I would go over, particularly Charles Caffey had replaced Paul Stevens at the time, and they'd have some plans.
Oh, particularly they did a lot of work down at Prairie View, landscape work, and down at Galveston.
And I went down, Estill borrowed me a time or two, and I went down to Galveston to help him out on some things.
Did you here have responsibility for the Chancellor's home?
Mm-hmm.
And what about the system building over on
What is that, 29th?
29th, I guess.
Yeah, that all came about after the merger.
I mean, that part of it.
Now, the chancellor's residence
We had a little problem there with one of the guys in the facilities planning, an architect over there, because they were designing that, and they were allocating like $20,000 for landscape.
And I told Bob, I said, Bob, this is a million-dollar house.
You can't do it.
He said, you'll take that and do it and like it.
And I said, we're busy.
You need to bid this one out.
And the landscape architect is a good friend of mine from San Antonio.
And he said, y'all need to do this.
I said, uh-uh.
I don't want to get caught in that trap.
And so they wound up doing a little fiddly job out there within that money, and nobody liked it, so they finally had to come out and get some more money and redo it.
And particularly after Perry Atkinson moved in out there, he had particularly that front terrace area got redone.
What the cost was?
Oh, God, I don't know.
Probably $50,000.
What about the big, I was gone at this time,
But the big argument, Bob Rucker being in the middle of it, about the oak trees over near the MSC, did those involve your?
Yeah.
Yeah.
Steve Hodge and Robert had come to me, you know, about the oak trees.
Robert Smith?
Robert Smith, he was, he was VP at the time.
And, uh, cause this was like an 80s, early 87 or so that, you know, this is going to take some trees.
And, uh, so we had some on both sides of the MSC and I said, well, I think the smaller ones could be relocated.
You know, that's, that's where I had hit it.
And Robert got into it and.
got to talking to a gentleman by the name of Al Krennic.
He's the guy that invented the tree spade and sold it to Vermeer for a pittance.
But anyway, and he was still digging trees by hand and had fabricated his original tree spade.
Al came up and looked at them and said, yeah, we can move these.
And then Robert got into it and talked to him.
And then suddenly, some of the bigger trees were added.
And I said, mm, I don't know about that.
And Al said, no, I think we can move them.
And so that's how that got started, because the trees that I wanted to move were some that I had planted in 1973 and four, particularly along Joe Route.
There were four or five of them.
And those are still alive.
and two or three plus some in Kane Park and one over by the administration building.
And maybe one or two of the others are still going, I don't know.
But I think, and I never could prove it, but I think there was some help because one or two of those trees went down overnight.
And that doesn't happen with lack of water.
We were going in
And they provided drainage in particularly large oak.
And in calculating the size of the ball and all like this, and we did a lot of preliminary pruning, you know, it had a good chance of working.
But we would water real heavily one day, and then the next day we'd put a little pump down to it, and we'd pump the water, the free water out, you know.
And we'd fed them.
And they were looking pretty, because we did this in probably January or so, January or February, because it was getting kind of late.
Yeah, probably February.
And I can remember showing my mother was alive then, and we went down for, I guess it was Mother's Day brunch.
And I walked her over and showed her the big trees that, you know, just, she was curious about it.
And they were in great shape then.
And then within,
10 days, and I usually personally checked them.
I looked at them on a daily basis because I knew if they died, there was going to be lots of flak generated on it.
And your thought is that perhaps somebody deliberately, what could they have done that would have killed them quicker?
Well, we had four large pipe.
They were big rectangular type boxed boxes that they boxed them in.
And they were set on gravel and I think set on a number of lateral PVC pipes to make sure they had plenty of air and drainage.
And on each corner, there was a big four-inch pipe to water in and to pump it out with because we'd gotten together and determined that that was the best approach to it.
And Al had moved a lot of trees bigger than that and gotten them to live, you know.

uh but they just they went down too quick and they browned just like that and normally you don't do that unless there's some kind of foreign agent in there but now am i correct in recalling that mr rucker thought one of those was a pet of president rudder yeah they're they kept
calling the big one the Rotor Oak.
And...
He didn't have any...
I didn't, uh-uh.
None of us could say, we don't know where that came from.
And I think that came from Robert.
Robert Smith?
Smith.
Now, Smith didn't want to move, or did he?
No, he did.
He did?
Yeah, yeah, he did.
But this was one that you thought was too big.
I thought it was too big.
There were three or four that... Robert talked to Al Krennic,
And then Al came back and said, well, they want to do this and this.
And I said, Al, I'm afraid those are too big.
Because what I want to do is like six or seven.
They were trees about like that.
I thought that was very easily doable.
And they were small enough we could get them around someplace and place them.
And we put three or four of them over in Kane Park.
And one of them is over by the entrance and exit to Lot 55.
And I can't think of where the other one is.
I knew those had a good root system because they'd been transplanted once or twice before we planted them.
That meant that they had a good, a very thick root system.
When you do that, trees are a lot more easily transplantable that way.

but now Bob would just rant and rave I kind of just backed off you know I said I agree they're too big you know but I don't know whether he thought I had the I was behind it or not but I was behind moving the small ones because I felt that was very very doable.
Among the goofy ideas I've had when some of the larger trees die

I've always thought, why wouldn't it be good for some Aggie that has a small little sawmill operation to come and get some of the trunks, saw it up, and to use it to make plaques and or picture frames out of that you'd sell to diehard Aggies?
Oh, yeah, yeah.
Because there's no value to live oak lumber.
No, as a lumber, no.
Because otherwise it ends up, I presume, as firewood.
Yeah.
And let some guy who's almost a hobby, let him do that.
What about, looking back, are there any changes in the way things were done that we might have done if we'd had all the experience we now have?
How could we have done things better?
Probably the primary thing was funding because the average person does not realize the kind of funding it takes to do what people want done.
About what percentage more would have made a difference?
I think if we'd had 15, 20 percent more.
That was before
that was in the early stages when they started cutting back on the formula.
But, and I don't even think the formula is a valid thing now, if you want to understand.
Did the formula get less and less?
Mm-hmm.
Formula got less and less, and then suddenly it, see, I kind of got out of the budget picture after the merger, because I wasn't allowed to in any of that.
Did grounds maintenance and
horticulture, floriculture, landscaping, did y'all ever get any of the PUFF money from the university fund?
It was all appropriated formula.
Right, right.
I tried, I think with, particularly with Chuck Cargill and Vandiver,
I worked up a program of landscape rejuvenation and renovation on the premise that landscapes wear out just like mechanical stuff and buildings and things like this.
And they always said, well, there's not enough.
We can't keep the buildings maintained.
And I understood, but I had to try.
But one of the things I wanted to do
and I tried to sell this to Joe Sugg, and he didn't like it, is I told him I thought we ought to collect acorns from the century oak and start, you know, an Aggie oak project.
I wrote up a couple of pages on that.
What happened to that proposal?
I think it went in his trash.
Oh.
Because he didn't like it.
Oh.
And he wanted to kill the...
the memorial tree program, which was, that was Bob Walker and I, after Bob got some emphasis from, who was chairman of the board, David Eller.
He lost a good friend, an ag from the valley, and that was the first memorial tree.
Bob and I talked about this a while.
I was
I was more interested in benches and things like this because we needed benches.
And so he called me up and he said, you know, we've been talking about this and I got some direct marching orders.
Come over and talk to me.
So we sat down and we worked out our memorial tree program.
Well, when Joe Sugg came, he said, we're going to do away with that.
And I said, no, we're not.
So I called Walker.
And I said, Bob, we've got a problem.
He said, I'm going to take him to lunch.
I said, good.
He said, you're coming.
We went to lunch up in the tower.
And in Bob's own very polite way, he explained it to him.
So I've never mentioned the memorial trees again.
He said, no, this is a program.
It's viable.
It's workable.
And I want this man on the other end of it.
And I guess Eller was still

chairman of the board maybe i'm not sure but he said this was initiated from the highest position and as long as i'm around it's going to stay here any questions as far as you were aware compared to the other areas underneath the vice president i'll call it for business were you all funded at approximately the same level were they also their budgets tight
Yeah, I think their budgets were tight.
I never did know much about the rest of the budgets because it really wasn't any of my...
But you didn't have the impression that y'all got cut more?
No.
There were times that, yeah, maybe we did get a little bit because we were probably a little more expendable to some degree than...
Let's say fiscal or personnel or something like that.
Some other things that just didn't work?
Some ideas that somebody had?
Oh, yeah.
The prairie film thing.
Prairie film?
Prairie film.
What that was, it's an epoxy coated aggregate.
It's one of those ideas that's fantastic on paper.
I always understood that General Ludeke thought that was a great idea.
Oh, yeah, he did.
Yeah, we hashed that out in his stuff, you know, and one of the landscape architects proposed it.
And it would have worked very well, except it started degenerating because of solar degeneration.
Light started breaking it down.
You know, like, and I don't know whether, of course,
with my background, I've had a lot of greenhouses with plastic on it.
And one day you just start looking at it and it just totally comes apart.
And that's what that was doing.

So we started a project of using interlocking pavers, you know, no mortar just, and that helped because I kept wanting to try to get as much air and water down to those tree roots and let people across, you know, without creating any more compaction and,
than necessary.
I guess we finally got rid of most of the epoxy, had to, just because it finally started breaking up.
Of course, somebody would get a vehicle up on it, and it was all broken up.
But that was one I thought was a really good idea.
And I think if it could have been kept in the shade and out of our intense sun, we'd have probably been OK.
But there's enough late and early morning light that it just started breaking.
And it all started happening.

within probably that all that was done in 70 74 5 and 6 and by 79 about three or four years and the areas of the real intense shade it lasted the longest so and that's what Goldwater and I came up with that it was a solar breakdown you know that it just uh it just started coming apart.
I've always liked when I go to the University of North Carolina
many, many of their sidewalks, I'll call them, are unmortared brick.
They tamp the sand underneath it.
They lay the bricks down as tree roots.
Oh, yeah.
They can come and go.
And then if they need to move the sidewalk, it's an instant thing.
See, what I tried to get going, after we started using the interlocking pavers, modular paving, and I tried to get...
I guess with Joe Estill, in a utility break, instead of going back with poured concrete,

use a gray interlocking paper you know and uh I mean because they can take those things and they've got them they've got them at DFW airport that all those big jets run on and all like this and it's on uh on uh granular road base you know granted but uh
They'll take an immense amount of traffic if they're properly based.
And I think they're a wonderful thing.
And I tried my best on the MSC thing to get the architects to consider doing something in that big plaza out there, you know, around the fountain, the brown brick.
I said, do something with some different colors and patterns and all like this.
I said, it's going to look like a roof scape.

I was right but the architect and I had so many confrontations over trees that the last couple reviews I would walk in and he would leave I mean it just I just was a thorn in his side because I wouldn't he said well we'll just take this tree out and I said now wait a minute why are you taking this tree out and
I finally got in, before I retired, I got in some trees over at Kyle Field.
The engineering guy that David Gallagher, he came and he said, I've got a problem.
Okay.
Are you asking me questions?
So we had a big tree that was going to be up against the face of the west end of the north side.
So I told David, I said, well, let's hold out.
We've got to save this.
